<display>
<type>book</type> 
<title>The &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Imperative</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2003</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264101197</identifier> 
<description>E-government is more about government than about "e". The spread of new information and communication technologies has spurred major changes at all levels of society and notably in citizen expectations. Governments have also been integrating those technologies into work practices to keep pace and enhance the policy outcomes, service quality, and responsiveness to citizens that determine their effectiveness. E-government initiatives can bolster government effectiveness in important ways like facilitating cross-agency cooperation on complex problems, fostering a customer focus for services, and building relationships with private sector partners. Delay in implementing e-government reforms can thus handicap economic development in this increasingly competitive, rapidly changing world.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004297499</lds02> 
<lds03>Executive Summary -- Chapter 1. Objectives, Scope, and Context -- Introduction -- Definitions -- Objectives -- Methodology -- Chapter 2. The Case for E-Government -- E-Government and Efficiency -- E-Government Improves Service Quality -- E-Government Increases Policy Effectiveness -- E-Government Contributes to Economic Policy Objectives -- E-Government Can Help Forward the Public Reform Agenda -- Citizen Engagement and Trust -- Chapter 3. External Barriers to E-Government -- Legislative and Regulatory Barriers -- Budgetary Barriers -- Technological Change -- The Digital Divide -- Chapter 4. Implementing E-Government -- Vision Statement and Plan -- Front Office -- Back Office -- What Could Go Wrong? -- Chapter 5. Conclusions and Future Challenges -- Bibliography -- Annex 1. Glossary -- Annex 2. E-Government Statistics -- Annex 3. ICT Diffusion and the Digital Divide</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30> 
<version>2</version></display>

<title>The &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Imperative</title> 
<description>E-government is more about government than about "e". The spread of new information and communication technologies has spurred major changes at all levels of society and notably in citizen expectations. Governments have also been integrating those technologies into work practices to keep pace and enhance the policy outcomes, service quality, and responsiveness to citizens that determine their effectiveness. E-government initiatives can bolster government effectiveness in important ways like facilitating cross-agency cooperation on complex problems, fostering a customer focus for services, and building relationships with private sector partners. Delay in implementing e-government reforms can thus handicap economic development in this increasingly competitive, rapidly changing world.</description> 
<general>OECD Publishing,</general> 
<general>10.1787/9789264101197-en</general> 
<general>[electronic resource] /</general> 
<general>(FR-PaOEC)9789264101197-en</general> 
<general>FRPaOEC9789264101197en</general> 
<general>AllDocuments</general> 
<sourceid>ndu_aleph</sourceid> 
<recordid>ndu_aleph004297499</recordid> 
<recordid>004297499</recordid> 
<recordid>4297499</recordid> 
<isbn>9789264101197</isbn> 
<isbn>9264101195</isbn> 
<toc>Executive Summary -- Chapter 1. Objectives, Scope, and Context -- Introduction -- Definitions -- Objectives -- Methodology -- Chapter 2. The Case for E-Government -- E-Government and Efficiency -- E-Government Improves Service Quality -- E-Government Increases Policy Effectiveness -- E-Government Contributes to Economic Policy Objectives -- E-Government Can Help Forward the Public Reform Agenda -- Citizen Engagement and Trust -- Chapter 3. External Barriers to E-Government -- Legislative and Regulatory Barriers -- Budgetary Barriers -- Technological Change -- The Digital Divide -- Chapter 4. Implementing E-Government -- Vision Statement and Plan -- Front Office -- Back Office -- What Could Go Wrong? -- Chapter 5. Conclusions and Future Challenges -- Bibliography -- Annex 1. Glossary -- Annex 2. E-Government Statistics -- Annex 3. ICT Diffusion and the Digital Divide</toc>

<enddate>20031231</enddate>

<abstract>E-government is more about government than about "e". The spread of new information and communication technologies has spurred major changes at all levels of society and notably in citizen expectations. Governments have also been integrating those technologies into work practices to keep pace and enhance the policy outcomes, service quality, and responsiveness to citizens that determine their effectiveness. E-government initiatives can bolster government effectiveness in important ways like facilitating cross-agency cooperation on complex problems, fostering a customer focus for services, and building relationships with private sector partners. Delay in implementing e-government reforms can thus handicap economic development in this increasingly competitive, rapidly changing world.</abstract>

<pub>OECD Publishing</pub>

<lds03>E-merging media: the future of communication / Valerie Feldmann, Axel Zerdick -- 1. CHANGING MEDIA: DIVERSIFICATION AND INDIVIDUALISATION -- Disintegration and reintegration in the media secotr: how business models are changing on account of digitalisation / Berthold Hass -- Media companies between multiple utilisation and individualisation: an analysis for static contents / Thomas Hess -- Multimedia and multidimensional: concepts of utilisation in the "age of digitalisation" / Hardy Dreier -- New technologies, new customers and the disruptive nature of the mobile Internet: evidence from the Japanese market / Jeffrey L. Funk -- Journalism in the face of developments in digital production / John Pavlik -- Spellbound by images / Siegfried Frey -- 2. CHANGING TECHNOLOGY: UBIQUITY AND MINIATURISATION -- Ubiquitous computing: scenarios from an informatised world / Friedemann Mattern -- Wireless Internet access: 3G vs. WiFi? / William Lehr, Lee W. McKnight -- That's what friends are for - ambient intelligence (Aml) and the information society in 2010 / K. Ducatel ... [et al.] -- Evolutionary perspectives / Klaus Schrape -- 3. CHANGING SOCIETY: INDIVIDUAL AND COLLECTIVE LIFE OPTIONS -- Virtual communities, space and mobility / Ilkka Tuomi -- Towards a sociological theory of the mobile phone / Hans Geser -- Mobile Europe: balancing a fast-changing society and Europe's socio-economic objectives / Martin Weber, Jean-Claude Burgelman -- The myth of the digital divide / Valerie Frissen -- The vanishing digital divide / Benjamin Compaine -- 4. CHANGING RULES: DEREGULATION AND REREGULATION -- Regulation and law / Ilkka Tuomi -- The history and current problems of intellectual property (1600-2000) / Hannes Siegrist -- Digital rights management: between author protection and the protection of innovation / Stefan Bechtold -- Does the Internet need a new competition policy? A global problem from a German point of view / Arnold Picot, Dominik K. Heger -- Towards an e-connected Europe / Stephen Coleman -- Regulation, media literacy and media civics / Roger Silverstone.</lds03> 
<lds05>Translated from German with the same title.</lds05>

<description>E-Governanceis regarded as one of the important subjects in the Information Society. Global e-governance for both public and private sectors is becoming significant in the world community. This title offers understanding of what information society or ubiquitous society is all about.</description>

<lds03>Una congettura sopra il libro Giusto -- Sul testo ebraico del Salmo 140 (141) -- Sul canone biblico di S. Epifanio -- D'alcuni frammenti esaplari sulla Va e VIa edizione greca della Bibbia -- Sul testo e sul senso di Eusebio H. e. VI 16 -- Anecdota apocrypha latina : una "Visio" ed una "Revelatio" d'Esdra con un decreto di Clemente Romano -- Due supposte lettere di Dionigi Alessandrino -- Anthimi Nicomediensis episcopi et martyris de sancta ecclesia -- Un foglio dell' Ilario papiraceo di Vienna -- Il carme Damasiano "de Davide" e la falsa corrispondenza di Damaso e Girolamo riguardo al Salterio -- I due "Trattati al popolo" di Priscilliano -- Appunti su Niceta ed Aniano traduttore di S. Giovanni Crisostomo -- Il commentario d' Esichio Gerosolimitano sui Salmi -- Per la vita e gli scritti di "Paolo il Persiano" -- Un'apologia antiellenica sotto forma di martirio -- La lettera di Pasquale I a Leone V sul culto delle sacre imagini.</lds03>

VI 16 -- Anecdota apocrypha latina : una "Visio" ed una "Revelatio" d'Esdra con un decreto di Clemente Romano -- Due supposte lettere di Dionigi Alessandrino -- Anthimi Nicomediensis episcopi et martyris de sancta ecclesia -- Un foglio dell' Ilario papiraceo di Vienna -- Il carme Damasiano "de Davide" e la falsa corrispondenza di Damaso e Girolamo riguardo al Salterio -- I due "Trattati al popolo" di Priscilliano -- Appunti su Niceta ed Aniano traduttore di S. <title><![CDATA[A memorial by the <span class="searchword">E</span>-l of K----ld-----<span class="searchword">e</span>, to His M-j--y, the 26th of May, 1753. Containing An Account, and Reasons of the Discontents and Divisions, that at present subsist among your M-j--y's most Dutiful, Faithful, Loyal H---<span class="searchword">e</span> of C--mm--ns, and devoted Protestant S-bj-Cts of I--l--d: Humbly offer'd to your M--j--y's Consideration. With The <span class="searchword">E</span>-l of H-ld-Ss's Letter, By his M--j--y's Command, to the L---d Ch-n-ll-r of I--l--d, in Answer to the <span class="searchword">E</span>--l of K-ld--c's Memorial.]]></title>

<lds03>Introduzione: La condanna di Roma in Hegel e in Heidegger / Franco Chiereghin -- Il ruolo di Cicerone nella interpretazione hegeliana della Romanitas / Franco Biasutti -- Due prestiti da Gibbon per la descrizione hegeliana dell'impero romano d'Oriente nelle / Giovanni Bonacina -- La critica heideggeriana al concetto di religio e il problema del Cristianesimo / Francesco Camera -- Hegel e Heidegger, Prima e dopo la romanità / Umberto Regina -- Heigegger: la Grecia, Roma e il Cristianesimo / Mario Ruggenni -- Diritto e giustizia tra intelletto e ragione. Hegel e il metodo della giurisprudenza romana / Stefano Fuselli -- Convergenze e diverenze nella definizione senecana e hegeliana di libertà / Francesca Menegoni -- Sul ruolo delle categorie logiche della limitazione nell'interpretazione hegeliana della Romanitas / Antonio Moretto -- L'origine e la sua dissoluzione: la Romanitas come problema in Hegel e Heidegger / Luca Illetterati -- La Romanitas fra Heidegger e Hegel / Leonardo Samonà.</lds03>

<toc>Introduzione: La condanna di Roma in Hegel e in Heidegger / Franco Chiereghin -- Il ruolo di Cicerone nella interpretazione hegeliana della Romanitas / Franco Biasutti -- Due prestiti da Gibbon per la descrizione hegeliana dell'impero romano d'Oriente nelle / Giovanni Bonacina -- La critica heideggeriana al concetto di religio e il problema del Cristianesimo / Francesco Camera -- Hegel e Heidegger, Prima e dopo la romanità / Umberto Regina -- Heigegger: la Grecia, Roma e il Cristianesimo / Mario Ruggenni -- Diritto e giustizia tra intelletto e ragione. Hegel e il metodo della giurisprudenza romana / Stefano Fuselli -- Convergenze e diverenze nella definizione senecana e hegeliana di libertà / Francesca Menegoni -- Sul ruolo delle categorie logiche della limitazione nell'interpretazione hegeliana della Romanitas / Antonio Moretto -- L'origine e la sua dissoluzione: la Romanitas come problema in Hegel e Heidegger / Luca Illetterati -- La Romanitas fra Heidegger e Hegel / Leonardo Samonà.</toc>

<type>book</type> 
<title>&lt;span class="searchword">E&lt;/span>-learning and the science of instruction : proven guidelines for consumers and designers of multimedia learning</title> 
<creator>Ruth Colvin Clark</creator> 
<contributor>Richard E. Mayer 1947-</contributor> 
<contributor>Wiley InterScience [Online service]</contributor> 
<edition>Fourth edition..</edition> 
<publisher>Hoboken, New Jersey : Wiley</publisher> 
<creationdate>2016, 2016</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V1119158680 (electronic bk.); $$CISBN $$V9781119158684 (electronic bk.); $$CISBN $$V9781119239086; $$CISBN $$V1119239087; $$CISBN $$V111808621X; $$CISBN $$V9781118086216; $$CISBN $$V9781119158677; $$CISBN $$V1119158672</identifier> 
<subject>Business education -- Computer-assisted instruction</subject> 
<subject>Web-based instruction</subject> 
<description>Annotation Thoroughly revised and updated, this third edition of the best-selling book offers a comprehensive review of multimedia learning for both users and designers. The book contains design principles that are written to increase learning while debunking many popular theories about good design. The book also contains the most current research and includes new topics (e-learning for educators, new delivery technologies, social media, and more) and offers helpful guidelines. The books many examples: create working multimedia that inform the research guidelines; have been update to include real-world screen captures; extend principles to illustrate their application to synchronous e-learning tools.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<lds01>John Wiley and Sons Wiley Frontlist All Obook 2016 and Ongoing</lds01> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004443379</lds02> 
<lds03>e-Learning: promise and pitfalls -- How do people learn from e-courses? -- Evidence-based practice -- Applying the multimedia principle: use words and graphics rather than words alone -- Applying the contiguity principle: align words to corresponding graphics -- Applying the modality principle: present words as audio narration rather than on-screen text -- Applying the redundancy principle: explain visuals with words in audio or text but not both -- Applying the coherence principle: adding extra material can hurt learning -- Applying the personalization and embodiment principles: use conversational style, polite wording, human voice, and virtual coaches -- Applying the segmenting and pretraining principles: managing complexity by breaking a lesson into parts -- Engagement in e-learning -- Leveraging examples in e-learning -- Does practice make perfect? -- Learning together virtually -- Who's in control? guidelines for e-learning navigation -- e-Learning to build thinking skills -- Learning with computer games -- Applying the guidelines. About This Book; Title page; Copyright; Dedication; Acknowledgments; Introduction; Chapter 1 e-Learning; Chapter Summary; What Is e-Learning?; Is e-Learning Better?; The Promises of e-Learning; The Pitfalls of e-Learning; <title>&lt;span class="searchword">E&lt;/span>-learning and the science of instruction : proven guidelines for consumers and designers of multimedia learning /</title> 
<description>Annotation Thoroughly revised and updated, this third edition of the best-selling book offers a comprehensive review of multimedia learning for both users and designers. The book contains design principles that are written to increase learning while debunking many popular theories about good design. The book also contains the most current research and includes new topics (e-learning for educators, new delivery technologies, social media, and more) and offers helpful guidelines. The books many examples: create working multimedia that inform the research guidelines; have been update to include real-world screen captures; extend principles to illustrate their application to synchronous e-learning tools.</description>

<subject>Web-based instruction.</subject> 
<subject>Online teaching</subject>

<subject>Web-based online instruction</subject>

<toc>e-Learning: promise and pitfalls -- How do people learn from e-courses? -- Evidence-based practice -- Applying the multimedia principle: use words and graphics rather than words alone -- Applying the contiguity principle: align words to corresponding graphics -- Applying the modality principle: present words as audio narration rather than on-screen text -- Applying the redundancy principle: explain visuals with words in audio or text but not both -- Applying the coherence principle: adding extra material can hurt learning -- Applying the personalization and embodiment principles: use conversational style, polite wording, human voice, and virtual coaches -- Applying the segmenting and pretraining principles: managing complexity by breaking a lesson into parts -- Engagement in e-learning -- Leveraging examples in e-learning -- Does practice make perfect? -- Learning together virtually -- Who's in control? guidelines for e-learning navigation -- e-Learning to build thinking skills -- Learning with computer games -- Applying the guidelines.</toc>

<title>Essere e persona : verso una fondazione fenomenologica di una metafisica classica e personalistica /</title>

<type>book</type> 
<title>&lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government for Better Government</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2005</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264018341</identifier> 
<description>Information and communication technology (ICT) offers an array of tools that can be used to help government services become more agile, responsive, seamless and accountable.  This book looks at new thinking and practice in OECD countries in five different areas:   Making electronic services more responsive to the needs of citizens and businesses; Improving the links between traditional and electronic services; Identifying common processes in government to achieve economies of scale, reduce duplication, and provide seamless services; Measuring and demonstrating the costs and benefits of ICT investments; Bringing a whole-of-government perspective to e-government initiatives.  </description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004298229</lds02> 
<lds03>Introduction -- Chapter 1. User-Focused E-Government -- Chapter 2. Multi-Channel Service Delivery -- Chapter 3. Approaches to Common Business Processes -- Chapter 4. The Business Case for E-Government -- Chapter 5. E-Government Coordination -- Chapter 6. Conclusion -- Annex: E-Government Statistics -- Bibliography</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30> 
</display>

<title>&lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government for Better Government</title> 
<description>Information and communication technology (ICT) offers an array of tools that can be used to help government services become more agile, responsive, seamless and accountable.  This book looks at new thinking and practice in OECD countries in five different areas:   Making electronic services more responsive to the needs of citizens and businesses; Improving the links between traditional and electronic services; Identifying common processes in government to achieve economies of scale, reduce duplication, and provide seamless services; Measuring and demonstrating the costs and benefits of ICT investments; Bringing a whole-of-government perspective to e-government initiatives.  </description> 
<general>OECD Publishing,</general> 
<general>10.1787/9789264018341-en</general> 
<general>[electronic resource] /</general> 
<general>(FR-PaOEC)9789264018341-en</general> 
<general>FRPaOEC9789264018341en</general> 
<general>AllDocuments</general> 
<sourceid>ndu_aleph</sourceid> 
<recordid>ndu_aleph004298229</recordid> 
<recordid>004298229</recordid> 
<recordid>4298229</recordid> 
<isbn>9789264018341</isbn> 
<isbn>9264018344</isbn> 
<toc>Introduction -- Chapter 1. User-Focused E-Government -- Chapter 2. Multi-Channel Service Delivery -- Chapter 3. Approaches to Common Business Processes -- Chapter 4. The Business Case for E-Government -- Chapter 5. E-Government Coordination -- Chapter 6. Conclusion -- Annex: E-Government Statistics -- Bibliography</toc> 
<creationdate>2005</creationdate> 
<startdate>20050101</startdate> 
<enddate>20051231</enddate>

<ristype>BOOK</ristype> 
<abstract>Information and communication technology (ICT) offers an array of tools that can be used to help government services become more agile, responsive, seamless and accountable.  This book looks at new thinking and practice in OECD countries in five different areas:   Making electronic services more responsive to the needs of citizens and businesses; Improving the links between traditional and electronic services; Identifying common processes in government to achieve economies of scale, reduce duplication, and provide seamless services; Measuring and demonstrating the costs and benefits of ICT investments; Bringing a whole-of-government perspective to e-government initiatives.  </abstract> 
<cop>Paris</cop> 
<pub>OECD Publishing</pub>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Egypt 2013</title> 
<description>This  report analyses e-government implementation in Egypt and presents a series of recommendations for action.</description> 
<general>OECD Publishing,</general> 
<general>10.1787/9789264178786-en</general> 
<general>[electronic resource] /</general>

<toc>Foreword -- Assessment and proposals for action -- Introduction -- The e-government context in Egypt -- Challenges to e-government -- E-government leadership in Egypt -- E-government service delivery architecture -- Outputs and outcomes of e-government -- New ways forward -- OECD E-Government Survey results -- Methodology -- Bibliography.</toc>

<type>book</type> 
<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Finland 2003</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2003</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264102613</identifier> 
<description>The first in a series of national e-government reviews, this book uses a common analytical framework developed by the OECD E-Government Project that will assist countries in evaluating their e-government policies, ensure international comparability of findings and systematically build up a body of empirical evidence regarding good e-government practices. </description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004298349</lds02> 
<lds03>Assessment and Proposals for Action -- PART I. COUNTRY STUDY  -- -Introduction -- Chapter 1. E-Government Structure and Context -- -The E-Government Administrative Structure and Key Players -- Chapter 2. The Case for E-Government -- -Public Reform Imperatives -- Spillover from the Information Society -- Demand for E-Government -- Chapter 3. Barriers to E-Government -- -Legislative and Regulatory Barriers -- Budgetary Barriers -- Technological Barriers -- The "Digital Divide" -- Chapter 4. Implementing E-Government -- -Vision and Planning -- Electronic Services -- E-Engagement -- Portals -- Back-Office Changes -- Monitoring and Evaluation of E-Government -- Chapter 5. Next Steps -- PART II. ANNEXES -- Chapter 6. Case Studies -- -Case Study 1: G2B Broker System for Reporting Business Data to Government (TYVI) -- Case Study 2: The Electronic Citizen Identification Card (FINEID) -- Case Study 3: The Citizen Portal -- Chapter 7. Appendix -- -Appendix 1: Finland's Political and Admnistrative System -- Appendix 2: Reports, Strategies, Decisions, and Acts Related to E-government -- Appendix 3: Synopsis of History and Key Decisions -- Appendix 4. Methodology -- Glossary -- List of Acronyms -- Bibliography</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30> 
</display>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Finland 2003</title> 
<description>The first in a series of national e-government reviews, this book uses a common analytical framework developed by the OECD E-Government Project that will assist countries in evaluating their e-government policies, ensure international comparability of findings and systematically build up a body of empirical evidence regarding good e-government practices. </description> 
<general>OECD Publishing,</general> 
<general>10.1787/9789264102613-en</general> 
<general>[electronic resource] /</general> 
<general>(FR-PaOEC)9789264102613-en</general> 
<general>FRPaOEC9789264102613en</general> 
<general>AllDocuments</general> 
<sourceid>ndu_aleph</sourceid> 
<recordid>ndu_aleph004298349</recordid> 
<recordid>004298349</recordid> 
<recordid>4298349</recordid> 
<isbn>9789264102613</isbn> 
<isbn>9264102612</isbn> 
<toc>Assessment and Proposals for Action -- PART I. COUNTRY STUDY  -- -Introduction -- Chapter 1. E-Government Structure and Context -- -The E-Government Administrative Structure and Key Players -- Chapter 2. The Case for E-Government -- -Public Reform Imperatives -- Spillover from the Information Society -- Demand for E-Government -- Chapter 3. Barriers to E-Government -- -Legislative and Regulatory Barriers -- Budgetary Barriers -- Technological Barriers -- The "Digital Divide" -- Chapter 4. Implementing E-Government -- -Vision and Planning -- Electronic Services -- E-Engagement -- Portals -- Back-Office Changes -- Monitoring and Evaluation of E-Government -- Chapter 5. Next Steps -- PART II. ANNEXES -- Chapter 6. Case Studies -- -Case Study 1: G2B Broker System for Reporting Business Data to Government (TYVI) -- Case Study 2: The Electronic Citizen Identification Card (FINEID) -- Case Study 3: The Citizen Portal -- Chapter 7. Appendix -- -Appendix 1: Finland's Political and Admnistrative System -- Appendix 2: Reports, Strategies, Decisions, and Acts Related to E-government -- Appendix 3: Synopsis of History and Key Decisions -- Appendix 4. Methodology -- Glossary -- List of Acronyms -- Bibliography</toc>

<enddate>20031231</enddate>

<abstract>The first in a series of national e-government reviews, this book uses a common analytical framework developed by the OECD E-Government Project that will assist countries in evaluating their e-government policies, ensure international comparability of findings and systematically build up a body of empirical evidence regarding good e-government practices. </abstract>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Mexico 2005</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2005</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264010727</identifier> 
<description>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Mexico from a whole-of-government perspective.  Mexico completed the initial phase of setting up and delivering e-government services successfully, but the continuing public demands to improve government have made the country realise the importance of refocusing the strategy to find a way of making e-government improve the overall quality of government. This report analyses and assesses these challenges and provides a set of proposals for action to deal with the most actual and pressing questions of e-government in Mexico.  It systematically looks at the structure and context for e-government, the case for e-government, external barriers to e-government, planning and leadership, organisational change, collaboration fostered by e-government, making government more customer-focused through e-government, and monitoring and evaluation.  This book includes case studies, a statistical annex, and a bibliography.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004294040</lds02> 
<lds03>Assessment and Proposals for Action -- Chapter 1. E-Government Structure and Context -- Chapter 2. The Case for E-Government -- Chapter 3. External Barriers to E-Government -- Chapter 4. Planning and Leadership -- Chapter 5. Organisational Change -- Chapter 6. E-Government Collaboration -- Chapter 7. User-Focused E-Government -- Chapter 8. Monitoring and Evaluation -- Next Steps -- Annex A. Case Studies -- Annex B. Statistical Annex -- Annex C. Methodology -- Annex D. Glossary -- Bibliography</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Mexico 2005</title> 
<description>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Mexico from a whole-of-government perspective.  Mexico completed the initial phase of setting up and delivering e-government services successfully, but the continuing public demands to improve government have made the country realise the importance of refocusing the strategy to find a way of making e-government improve the overall quality of government. This report analyses and assesses these challenges and provides a set of proposals for action to deal with the most actual and pressing questions of e-government in Mexico.  It systematically looks at the structure and context for e-government, the case for e-government, external barriers to e-government, planning and leadership, organisational change, collaboration fostered by e-government, making government more customer-focused through e-government, and monitoring and evaluation.  This book includes case studies, a statistical annex, and a bibliography.</description>

<abstract>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Mexico from a whole-of-government perspective.  Mexico completed the initial phase of setting up and delivering e-government services successfully, but the continuing public demands to improve government have made the country realise the importance of refocusing the strategy to find a way of making e-government improve the overall quality of government. This report analyses and assesses these challenges and provides a set of proposals for action to deal with the most actual and pressing questions of e-government in Mexico.  It systematically looks at the structure and context for e-government, the case for e-government, external barriers to e-government, planning and leadership, organisational change, collaboration fostered by e-government, making government more customer-focused through e-government, and monitoring and evaluation.  This book includes case studies, a statistical annex, and a bibliography.</abstract> 
<cop>Paris</cop> 
<pub>OECD Publishing</pub>

<type>book</type> 
<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Denmark 2006</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2006</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264012356</identifier> 
<description>This book presents a systematic overview of the development of and challenges facing e-government in Denmark.  It includes an examination of the context and structure within which e-government operates; the case for e-government, and external barriers to e-government.  It then examines planning and leadership issues, organisational change, common frameworks and collaboration, user focus, and monitoring and evaluation.  Two case studies  and six annexes supplement the main report.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004293944</lds02> 
<lds03>Summary Assessment and Proposals for Action -- Chapter 1. E-Government Context and Structure -- Chapter 2. The Case of E-Government -- Chapter 3. External Barriers -- Chapter 4. Planning and Leadership -- Chapter 5. Organisational Change -- Chapter 6. Common Frameworks and Collaboration -- Chapter 7. User Focus -- Chapter 8. Monitoring and Evaluation -- Case Study 1. Standards-Based E-Government in the Health Sector -- Case Study 2. Achieving E-Government Readiness - eDay -- Annex A. Overview of Political and Administrative System -- Annex B. Institutional Context and Public Governance Arrangements -- Annex C. Relevant Reports, Strategies, Decisions, and Acts -- Annex D. Policies, Strategies, and Plans Related to E-Government -- Annex E. Methodology -- Annex F. Glossary -- Bibliography</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30> 
</display>

<creatorcontrib>Ching chi ho tso fa chan tsu chih</creatorcontrib> 
<creatorcontrib>Majanduskoostöö ja Arengu Organisatsioon</creatorcontrib> 
<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Denmark 2006</title> 
<description>This book presents a systematic overview of the development of and challenges facing e-government in Denmark.  It includes an examination of the context and structure within which e-government operates; the case for e-government, and external barriers to e-government.  It then examines planning and leadership issues, organisational change, common frameworks and collaboration, user focus, and monitoring and evaluation.  Two case studies  and six annexes supplement the main report.</description> 
<general>OECD Publishing,</general> 
<general>10.1787/9789264012356-en</general> 
<general>[electronic resource] /</general> 
<general>(FR-PaOEC)9789264012356-en</general> 
<general>FRPaOEC9789264012356en</general> 
<general>AllDocuments</general> 
<sourceid>ndu_aleph</sourceid> 
<recordid>ndu_aleph004293944</recordid> 
<recordid>004293944</recordid> 
<recordid>4293944</recordid> 
<isbn>9789264012356</isbn> 
<isbn>9264012354</isbn> 
<toc>Summary Assessment and Proposals for Action -- Chapter 1. E-Government Context and Structure -- Chapter 2. The Case of E-Government -- Chapter 3. External Barriers -- Chapter 4. Planning and Leadership -- Chapter 5. Organisational Change -- Chapter 6. Common Frameworks and Collaboration -- Chapter 7. User Focus -- Chapter 8. Monitoring and Evaluation -- Case Study 1. Standards-Based E-Government in the Health Sector -- Case Study 2. Achieving E-Government Readiness - eDay -- Annex A. Overview of Political and Administrative System -- Annex B. Institutional Context and Public Governance Arrangements -- Annex C. Relevant Reports, Strategies, Decisions, and Acts -- Annex D. Policies, Strategies, and Plans Related to E-Government -- Annex E. Methodology -- Annex F. Glossary -- Bibliography</toc>

<startdate>20060101</startdate> 
<enddate>20061231</enddate>

<aucorp>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development</aucorp> 
<btitle>OECD e-Government Studies: Denmark 2006</btitle> 
<seriestitle>OECD e-Government Studies</seriestitle>

<format>book</format> 
<ristype>BOOK</ristype> 
<abstract>This book presents a systematic overview of the development of and challenges facing e-government in Denmark.  It includes an examination of the context and structure within which e-government operates; the case for e-government, and external barriers to e-government.  It then examines planning and leadership issues, organisational change, common frameworks and collaboration, user focus, and monitoring and evaluation.  Two case studies  and six annexes supplement the main report.</abstract> 
<cop>Paris</cop> 
<pub>OECD Publishing</pub>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Turkey 2007</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2007</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264028456</identifier> 
<description>Turkey’s e-government efforts received new emphasis in the last three years. The election of a new government brought forward an agenda including public sector modernisation using e-government. Turkey has since made considerable progress with e-government. This review identifies several strategic opportunities. One opportunity is to stimulate the provision of e-services and e-commerce by increasing access to high-speed Internet throughout the country. A second opportunity is to skip the initial stages of e-government applications -- characterised by isolated islands of development -- and instead promote a more "joined up" government. A third opportunity is to use the existing base of 46 million mobile telephones as a communication channel between the government and its citizens. The review also identifies several major challenges. One challenge is bridging the digital divide between urban and rural populations, men and women, and young and old. A second challenge is public sector modernisation in terms of increased transparency and accountability. A third challenge is making sure that investments in e-government are valuable, i.e. that benefits are larger than costs.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Turkey 2007</title> 
<description>Turkey’s e-government efforts received new emphasis in the last three years. The election of a new government brought forward an agenda including public sector modernisation using e-government. Turkey has since made considerable progress with e-government. This review identifies several strategic opportunities. One opportunity is to stimulate the provision of e-services and e-commerce by increasing access to high-speed Internet throughout the country. A second opportunity is to skip the initial stages of e-government applications -- characterised by isolated islands of development -- and instead promote a more "joined up" government. A third opportunity is to use the existing base of 46 million mobile telephones as a communication channel between the government and its citizens. The review also identifies several major challenges. One challenge is bridging the digital divide between urban and rural populations, men and women, and young and old. A second challenge is public sector modernisation in terms of increased transparency and accountability. A third challenge is making sure that investments in e-government are valuable, i.e. that benefits are larger than costs.</description>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Netherlands 2007</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2007</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264030299</identifier> 
<description>Rather than pursuing e-government as an end in itself, the Netherlands is seeking to use ICT tools to reduce administrative burdens and improve service delivery. Internationally, the Netherlands is at the forefront of administrative burden reduction, which is a major political priority and an important justification for e-government development. This volume examines questions such as whether the goal of reducing administrative burdens is sufficient in itself for e-government to transform public administrations. Further, how can the public sector build partnerships across levels of government to deliver ICT-enabled end-to-end services that simplify the relationship with citizens and businesses? This report is in English only. However, a French translation of the Assessment and Proposals for Action has been included in this volume.  </description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Netherlands 2007</title> 
<description>Rather than pursuing e-government as an end in itself, the Netherlands is seeking to use ICT tools to reduce administrative burdens and improve service delivery. Internationally, the Netherlands is at the forefront of administrative burden reduction, which is a major political priority and an important justification for e-government development. This volume examines questions such as whether the goal of reducing administrative burdens is sufficient in itself for e-government to transform public administrations. Further, how can the public sector build partnerships across levels of government to deliver ICT-enabled end-to-end services that simplify the relationship with citizens and businesses? This report is in English only. However, a French translation of the Assessment and Proposals for Action has been included in this volume.  </description>

<abstract>Rather than pursuing e-government as an end in itself, the Netherlands is seeking to use ICT tools to reduce administrative burdens and improve service delivery. Internationally, the Netherlands is at the forefront of administrative burden reduction, which is a major political priority and an important justification for e-government development. This volume examines questions such as whether the goal of reducing administrative burdens is sufficient in itself for e-government to transform public administrations. Further, how can the public sector build partnerships across levels of government to deliver ICT-enabled end-to-end services that simplify the relationship with citizens and businesses? This report is in English only. However, a French translation of the Assessment and Proposals for Action has been included in this volume.  </abstract>

<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2005</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264010680</identifier> 
<description>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Norway from a whole-of-government perspective. It looks at the progress to date and the remaining challenges the Norwegian government faces in implementing e-government and provides a detailed analysis of the e-government policy cycle, focusing on the role of the central state as a policy actor. The report also provides proposals for action to improve the delivery of electronic services to citizens, to understand public demand for online services and participation in government, to develop frameworks for monitoring and evaluation of e-government, to respond to agencies’ demands for more central guidance, and to improve co-ordination.   </description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004297026</lds02> 
<lds03>Assessment and Proposals for Action -- E-government Structure and Context -- The Case for E-government -- External Barriers to E-government -- Planning and Leadership -- Organisational Change -- Common Frameworks and Collaboration -- User-focused E-government -- Monitoring and Evaluation -- Case Study 1. From Data Collection to Multiple Citizen Services -- Case Study 2. From Portal Project to Agency -- Annexes.</lds03> 
<lds30>OECD e-Government Studies,</lds30>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Norway 2005</title> 
<description>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Norway from a whole-of-government perspective. It looks at the progress to date and the remaining challenges the Norwegian government faces in implementing e-government and provides a detailed analysis of the e-government policy cycle, focusing on the role of the central state as a policy actor. The report also provides proposals for action to improve the delivery of electronic services to citizens, to understand public demand for online services and participation in government, to develop frameworks for monitoring and evaluation of e-government, to respond to agencies’ demands for more central guidance, and to improve co-ordination.   </description>

<abstract>This review is the first study that undertakes an in-depth analysis of e-government in Norway from a whole-of-government perspective. It looks at the progress to date and the remaining challenges the Norwegian government faces in implementing e-government and provides a detailed analysis of the e-government policy cycle, focusing on the role of the central state as a policy actor. The report also provides proposals for action to improve the delivery of electronic services to citizens, to understand public demand for online services and participation in government, to develop frameworks for monitoring and evaluation of e-government, to respond to agencies’ demands for more central guidance, and to improve co-ordination.   </abstract>

<title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Hungary 2007</title> 
<creator>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</creator> 
<contributor>Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.</contributor> 
<publisher>Paris : OECD Publishing</publisher> 
<creationdate>2007</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource.</format> 
<identifier>$$CISBN $$V9789264030527</identifier> 
<description>E-Government in Hungary has been driven by the overarching national goal to integrate Hungary in the European Union. Strong political leadership has lead to results in a short space of time, including the online availability of 20 core e-government services benchmarked by the EU, as well as other transactional services.  The review draws several important lessons from the Hungarian experience: Hungary has moved forward by adopting international good practices, rather than re-inventing the wheel. In order to continue progress, however, Hungary needs to focus on the bigger picture which means using e-government to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the public sector, i.e. better government, not more government.  This review also identifies the challenges that Hungary will face in order to meet these new objectives.</description> 
<language>eng</language> 
<relation>$$Cseries $$VOECD e-Government Studies, 1990-1054.</relation> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph004296495</lds02>

Hungary Political and Adminstrative System -- Annex D. E-Government Reports, Decisions, Strategies, and Acts -- Annex E. Case Studies -- Annex F. Methodology -- Annex G. Glossary -- Annex H. <title>OECD &lt;span class="searchword">e&lt;/span>-Government Studies: Hungary 2007</title> 
<description>E-Government in Hungary has been driven by the overarching national goal to integrate Hungary in the European Union. Strong political leadership has lead to results in a short space of time, including the online availability of 20 core e-government services benchmarked by the EU, as well as other transactional services.  The review draws several important lessons from the Hungarian experience: Hungary has moved forward by adopting international good practices, rather than re-inventing the wheel. In order to continue progress, however, Hungary needs to focus on the bigger picture which means using e-government to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the public sector, i.e. better government, not more government.  This review also identifies the challenges that Hungary will face in order to meet these new objectives.</description>

<abstract>E-Government in Hungary has been driven by the overarching national goal to integrate Hungary in the European Union. Strong political leadership has lead to results in a short space of time, including the online availability of 20 core e-government services benchmarked by the EU, as well as other transactional services.  The review draws several important lessons from the Hungarian experience: Hungary has moved forward by adopting international good practices, rather than re-inventing the wheel. In order to continue progress, however, Hungary needs to focus on the bigger picture which means using e-government to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the public sector, i.e. better government, not more government.  This review also identifies the challenges that Hungary will face in order to meet these new objectives.</abstract> 
<cop>Paris</cop> 
<pub>OECD Publishing</pub> 
</addata>

<title>Septet in &lt;span class="searchword">E&lt;/span>-flat</title> 
<creator>Franz Lachner 1803-1890.</creator> 
<contributor>Franz Beyer 1922-</contributor> 
<contributor>Naxos Digital Services.</contributor> 
<contributor>Ensemble Villa Musica.</contributor> 
<publisher>Hong Kong : Marco Polo</publisher> 
<creationdate>p1989</creationdate> 
<format>1 online resource (1 sound file)..</format> 
<subject>Septets [Clarinet, flute, horn, violin, viola, violoncello, double bass]</subject> 
<subject>Quintets [Clarinet, violins [2], viola, cello]</subject> 
<unititle>Septet, woodwinds, horn, strings, E♭ major</unititle> 
<lds01>The 1st work, completed by Franz Beyer, is for clarinet, flute, horn, violin, viola, violoncello, and double bass; the 2nd for clarinet, 2 violins, viola, and violoncello.</lds01> 
<lds01>Ensemble Villa Musica (Jean Claude Gerard, flute ; Ulf Rodenhäuser, clarinet ; Ernö Sebestyen, Albert Boesen, violin ; Enrique Santiago, viola ; Marie-Luise Neunecker, horn ; Martin ostertag, violoncello ; Wolfgang Güttler, double bass).</lds01> 
<lds01>Recorded between Sept. 26 and Oct. 4, 1988, at Tonstudio fvan Geest, Heidelberg.</lds01> 
<lds02>ndu_aleph003825117</lds02> 
<lds03>Clarinet Quintet in E flat major, Op. 102 / Robert Fuchs (Villa Musica Ensemble) -- Septet in E flat major / Franz Paul Lachner (Villa Musica Ensemble).</lds03> 
<lds31>Lachner, Franz, 1803-1890. -- Septet, -- woodwinds, horn, strings, -- E♭ major</lds31> 
<lds31>Fuchs, Robert, 1847-1927.-- Quintet, -- clarinet, violins (2), viola, cello, -- op. 102, -- E♭ major</lds31>

<lds30>Quaderni di "Musica e storia" ; ~~ 3</lds30> 
<lds31>Petrobelli, Pierluigi.-- Manoscritto liturgico del XIX secolo di origine toscana con polifonie primitive.</lds31> 
<lds31>Boscolo, Lucia.-- Composizione a 4 voci in notazione quadrata ne codice fiorentino di Bruxelles 27766.</lds31> 
<lds31>Catucci, Rossana.-- Tre composizioni di polifonia semplice in manoscritti tardivi di Putignano e Locorotondo (Puglia).</lds31> 
<lds31>Pugliese, Annunziato.-- Polifonia semplice nelle fonti calabresi.</lds31> 
<lds31>Fiori, Alessandra, 1962--- Insolita fonte per lo studio delle polifonie primitive.</lds31> 
<lds31>Rankin, Susan.-- Between oral and written: Thirteenth-century Italian sources of poliphony.</lds31> 
<lds31>Haggh, Barbara Helen, 1955--- Simple poliphony from Ghent: representative or exceptional?</lds31> 
<lds31>Celestini, Federico.-- Polifonie del codice A-Rei 60 : Osservazioni sulle modalità di trasmissione.</lds31> 
<lds31>Rusconi, Angelo.-- Testimonianze di polifonia semplice nelle biblioteche di Bergamo.</lds31> 
<lds31>Szendrei, Janka.-- Oralità und scrittura im Lichte einer Genealogie-Aufzeichung.</lds31> 
<lds31>Dobzsay, László.-- Liturgical polyphony in the medieval Hungary.</lds31> 
<lds31>Ruini, Cesare.-- Foni settecentesche di polifonia semplice a Trento: un modello di trasmissione.</lds31> 
<lds31>Baroffio, Giacomo.-- Polifonie primitive nella tradizione manoscritta italiana : Appunti di ricerca.</lds31> 
<lds31>Luisi, Francesco.-- Bicinia in musica picta.</lds31> 
<lds31>Montagnier, Jean-Paul.-- Chant sur le livre en France aux XVIIe et XVIIIe siècles : De la survivance d'une tradition orale ancienne à l' avènement d' un genre écrit.</lds31> 
<lds31>Lovato, Antonio.-- Polifonie semplici in fonti e trattati italiani dei secoli XVII-XIX.</lds31> 
<lds31>Mele, Giampaolo.-- Vox viva versus vox mortua : Problemi storici sulle fonti della polivocalità liturgica sarda tra medioevo e età spagnola.</lds31>
